# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: complex-systems
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:complex-systems/bifurcation-theory] The name "bifurcation" was first introduced by Henri Poincaré in 1885 in the first paper in mathematics showing such a behavior.
[src:complex-systems/bifurcation-theory] A local bifurcation occurs when a parameter change causes the stability of an equilibrium (or fixed point) to change.
[src:complex-systems/bifurcation-theory] In continuous systems, this corresponds to the real part of an eigenvalue of an equilibrium passing through zero.
[src:complex-systems/bifurcation-theory] In discrete systems (described by maps), this corresponds to a fixed point having a Floquet multiplier with modulus equal to one.
[src:complex-systems/bifurcation-theory] In both cases, the equilibrium is *non-hyperbolic* at the bifurcation point.
[src:complex-systems/bifurcation-theory] The topological changes in the phase portrait of the system can be confined to arbitrarily small neighbourhoods of the bifurcating fixed points by moving the bifurcation parameter close to the bifurcation point (hence "local").
[src:complex-systems/bifurcation-theory] If the eigenvalue is equal to zero, the bifurcation is a steady-state bifurcation, but if the eigenvalue is non-zero but purely imaginary, this is a Hopf bifurcation.
[src:complex-systems/bifurcation-theory] For discrete dynamical systems, consider the system $x_{n+1}=f(x_{n},\lambda ).$ Then a local bifurcation occurs at $(x_{0},\lambda _{0})$ if the matrix ${\textrm {d}}f_{x_{0},\lambda _{0}}$ has an eigenvalue with modulus equal to one.
[src:complex-systems/bifurcation-theory] If the eigenvalue is equal to one, the bifurcation is either a saddle-node (often called fold bifurcation in maps), transcritical or pitchfork bifurcation.
[src:complex-systems/bifurcation-theory] If the eigenvalue is equal to −1, it is a period-doubling (or flip) bifurcation, and otherwise, it is a Hopf bifurcation.
[src:complex-systems/bifurcation-theory] Global bifurcations occur when "larger" invariant sets, such as periodic orbits, collide with equilibria.
[src:complex-systems/bifurcation-theory] This causes changes in the topology of the trajectories in the phase space which cannot be confined to a small neighbourhood, as is the case with local bifurcations.
[src:complex-systems/bifurcation-theory] In fact, the changes in topology extend out to an arbitrarily large distance (hence "global").
[src:complex-systems/bifurcation-theory] Global bifurcations can also involve more complicated sets such as chaotic attractors (e.g. crises).
[src:complex-systems/bifurcation-theory] The codimension of a bifurcation is the number of parameters which must be varied for the bifurcation to occur.
[src:complex-systems/bifurcation-theory] This corresponds to the codimension of the parameter set for which the bifurcation occurs within the full space of parameters.
[src:complex-systems/bifurcation-theory] Saddle-node bifurcations and Hopf bifurcations are the only generic local bifurcations which are really codimension-one (the others all having higher codimension).
[src:complex-systems/bifurcation-theory] However, transcritical and pitchfork bifurcations are also often thought of as codimension-one, because the normal forms can be written with only one parameter.
[src:complex-systems/bifurcation-theory] An example of a well-studied codimension-two bifurcation is the Bogdanov–Takens bifurcation.
[src:complex-systems/bifurcation-theory] Bifurcation theory has been applied to connect quantum systems to the dynamics of their classical analogues in atomic systems, molecular systems, and resonant tunneling diodes.
[src:complex-systems/bifurcation-theory] Bifurcation theory has also been applied to the study of laser dynamics and a number of theoretical examples which are difficult to access experimentally such as the kicked top and coupled quantum wells.
[src:complex-systems/bifurcation-theory] The dominant reason for the link between quantum systems and bifurcations in the classical equations of motion is that at bifurcations, the signature of classical orbits becomes large, as Martin Gutzwiller points out in his classic work on quantum chaos.
[src:complex-systems/bifurcation-theory] Many kinds of bifurcations have been studied with regard to links between classical and quantum dynamics including saddle node bifurcations, Hopf bifurcations, umbilic bifurcations, period doubling bifurcations, reconnection bifurcations, tangent bifurcations, and cusp bifurcations.
[src:complex-systems/complex-system] A **complex system** is a system composed of many components that interact with one another.
[src:complex-systems/complex-system] The behavior of a complex system is intrinsically difficult to model due to the dependencies, competitions, relationships, and other types of interactions between their parts or between a given system and its environment.
[src:complex-systems/complex-system] Systems that are "complex" have distinct properties that arise from these relationships, such as nonlinearity, emergence, spontaneous order, adaptation, and feedback loops, among others.
[src:complex-systems/complex-system] Because such systems appear in a wide variety of fields, the commonalities among them have become the topic of their independent area of research.
[src:complex-systems/complex-system] In many cases, it is useful to represent such a system as a network (graph) where the nodes represent the components and links represent their interactions.
[src:complex-systems/complex-system] The term *complex systems* often refers to the study of complex systems, which is an approach to science that investigates how relationships between a system's parts give rise to its collective behaviors and how the system interacts and forms relationships with its environment.
[src:complex-systems/complex-system] As an interdisciplinary domain, complex systems draw contributions from many different fields, such as the study of self-organization and critical phenomena from physics, of spontaneous order from the social sciences, chaos from mathematics, adaptation from biology, and many others.
[src:complex-systems/complex-system] *Complex systems* is therefore often used as a broad term encompassing a research approach to problems in many diverse disciplines, including statistical physics, information theory, nonlinear dynamics, anthropology, computer science, meteorology, sociology, economics, psychology, and biology.
[src:complex-systems/complex-system] Complex adaptive systems are special cases of complex systems that are adaptive in that they have the capacity to change and learn from experience.
[src:complex-systems/complex-system] A system is **decomposable** if the parts of the system (subsystems) are independent from each other, for example the model of a perfect gas consider the relations among molecules negligible.
[src:complex-systems/complex-system] In a **nearly decomposable** system, the interactions between subsystems are weak but not negligible, this is often the case in social systems.
[src:complex-systems/complex-system] Conceptually, a system is nearly decomposable if the variables composing it can be separated into classes and subclasses, if these variables are independent for many functions but affect each other, and if the whole system is greater than the parts.
[src:complex-systems/complex-system] The components of a complex system may themselves be complex systems.
[src:complex-systems/complex-system] The arrangement of interactions within complex bipartite networks may be nested as well.
[src:complex-systems/complex-system] ecological and organisational networks of mutually beneficial interactions were found to have a nested structure.
[src:complex-systems/complex-system] This structure promotes indirect facilitation and a system's capacity to persist under increasingly harsh circumstances as well as the potential for large-scale systemic regime shifts.
[src:complex-systems/complex-system] which have many local interactions and a smaller number of inter-area connections are often employed.
[src:complex-systems/complex-system] projections between regions inside the cortex and to other brain regions.
[src:complex-systems/complex-system] , which is to say that while the results may be sufficiently determined by the activity of the systems' basic constituents, they may have properties that can only be studied at a higher level.
[src:complex-systems/complex-system] features across aquatic and terrestrial ecosystems when studied at the level of clustered 'trophic' species.
[src:complex-systems/complex-system] and mound building is a property that emerges from the collection of termites and needs to be analyzed at a different level.
[src:complex-systems/complex-system] ), a proportional effect, or even no effect at all.
[src:complex-systems/complex-system] The effects of an element's behavior are fed back in such a way that the element itself is altered.
[src:complex-systems/complex-system] Warren Weaver published an essay on "Science and Complexity", exploring the diversity of problem types by contrasting problems of simplicity, disorganized complexity, and organized complexity.
[src:complex-systems/complex-system] While the explicit study of complex systems dates at least to the 1970s, the first research institute focused on complex systems, the Santa Fe Institute, was founded in 1984.
[src:complex-systems/complex-system] Early Santa Fe Institute participants included physics Nobel laureates Murray Gell-Mann and Philip Anderson, economics Nobel laureate Kenneth Arrow, and Manhattan Project scientists George Cowan and Herb Anderson.
[src:complex-systems/complex-system] Today, there are over 50 institutes and research centers focusing on complex systems.
[src:complex-systems/complex-system] Since the late 1990s, the interest of mathematical physicists in researching economic phenomena has been on the rise.
[src:complex-systems/complex-system] The proliferation of cross-disciplinary research with the application of solutions originated from the physics epistemology has entailed a gradual paradigm shift in the theoretical articulations and methodological approaches in economics, primarily in financial economics.
[src:complex-systems/complex-system] The development has resulted in the emergence of a new branch of discipline, namely "econophysics", which is broadly defined as a cross-discipline that applies statistical physics methodologies which are mostly based on the complex systems theory and the chaos theory for economics analysis.
[src:complex-systems/complex-system] The 2021 Nobel Prize in Physics was awarded to Syukuro Manabe, Klaus Hasselmann, and Giorgio Parisi for their work to understand complex systems.
[src:complex-systems/complex-system] Their work was used to create more accurate computer models of the effect of global warming on the Earth's climate.
[src:complex-systems/complex-system] The traditional approach to dealing with complexity is to reduce or constrain it.
[src:complex-systems/complex-system] Typically, this involves compartmentalization: dividing a large system into separate parts.
[src:complex-systems/complex-system] Organizations, for instance, divide their work into departments that each deal with separate issues.
[src:complex-systems/complex-system] Engineering systems are often designed using modular components.
[src:complex-systems/complex-system] However, modular designs become susceptible to failure when issues arise that bridge the divisions.
[src:complex-systems/complex-system] Jane Jacobs described cities as being a problem in organized complexity in 1961, citing Dr.
[src:complex-systems/complex-system] As an example, she explains how an abundance of factors interplay into how various urban spaces lead to a diversity of interactions, and how changing those factors can change how the space is used, and how well the space supports the functions of the city.
[src:complex-systems/complex-system] She further illustrates how cities have been severely damaged when approached as a problem in simplicity by replacing organized complexity with simple and predictable spaces, such as Le Corbusier's "Radiant City" and Ebenezer Howard's "Garden City".
[src:complex-systems/complex-system] Since then, others have written at length on the complexity of cities.
[src:complex-systems/complex-system] Over the last decades, within the emerging field of complexity economics, new predictive tools have been developed to explain economic growth.
[src:complex-systems/complex-system] Such is the case with the models built by the Santa Fe Institute in 1989 and the more recent economic complexity index (ECI), introduced by the MIT physicist Cesar A.
[src:complex-systems/complex-system] Hidalgo and the Harvard economist Ricardo Hausmann.
[src:complex-systems/complex-system] Recurrence quantification analysis has been employed to detect the characteristic of business cycles and economic development.
[src:complex-systems/complex-system] To this end, Orlando et al. developed the so-called recurrence quantification correlation index (RQCI) to test correlations of RQA on a sample signal and then investigated the application to business time series.
[src:complex-systems/complex-system] The said index has been proven to detect hidden changes in time series.
[src:complex-systems/complex-system] Further, Orlando et al., over an extensive dataset, shown that recurrence quantification analysis may help in anticipating transitions from laminar (i.e. regular) to turbulent (i.e. chaotic) phases such as USA GDP in 1949, 1953, etc.
[src:complex-systems/complex-system] Last but not least, it has been demonstrated that recurrence quantification analysis can detect differences between macroeconomic variables and highlight hidden features of economic dynamics.
[src:complex-systems/complex-system] Healthcare systems are prime examples of complex systems, characterized by interactions among diverse stakeholders, such as patients, providers, policymakers, and researchers, across various sectors like health, government, community, and education.
[src:complex-systems/complex-system] These systems demonstrate properties like non-linearity, emergence, adaptation, and feedback loops.
[src:complex-systems/complex-system] Complexity science in healthcare frames knowledge translation as a dynamic and interconnected network of processes—problem identification, knowledge creation, synthesis, implementation, and evaluation—rather than a linear or cyclical sequence.
[src:complex-systems/complex-system] Such approaches emphasize the importance of understanding and leveraging the interactions within and between these processes and stakeholders to optimize the creation and movement of knowledge.
[src:complex-systems/complex-system] By acknowledging the complex, adaptive nature of healthcare systems, complexity science advocates for continuous stakeholder engagement, transdisciplinary collaboration, and flexible strategies to effectively translate research into practice.
[src:complex-systems/complex-system] Complexity science has been applied to living organisms, and in particular to biological systems.
[src:complex-systems/complex-system] Within the emerging field of fractal physiology, bodily signals, such as heart rate or brain activity, are characterized using entropy or fractal indices.
[src:complex-systems/complex-system] The goal is often to assess the state and the health of the underlying system, and diagnose potential disorders and illnesses.
[src:complex-systems/complex-system] Complex systems theory is related to chaos theory, which in turn has its origins more than a century ago in the work of the French mathematician Henri Poincaré.
[src:complex-systems/complex-system] Chaos is sometimes viewed as extremely complicated information, rather than as an absence of order.
[src:complex-systems/complex-system] Chaotic systems remain deterministic, though their long-term behavior can be difficult to predict with any accuracy.
[src:complex-systems/complex-system] With perfect knowledge of the initial conditions and the relevant equations describing the chaotic system's behavior, one can theoretically make perfectly accurate predictions of the system, though in practice this is impossible to do with arbitrary accuracy.
[src:complex-systems/complex-system] The emergence of complex systems theory shows a domain between deterministic order and randomness which is complex.
[src:complex-systems/complex-system] This is referred to as the "edge of chaos".
[src:complex-systems/complex-system] When one analyzes complex systems, sensitivity to initial conditions, for example, is not an issue as important as it is within chaos theory, in which it prevails.
[src:complex-systems/complex-system] As stated by Colander, the study of complexity is the opposite of the study of chaos.
[src:complex-systems/complex-system] Complexity is about how a huge number of extremely complicated and dynamic sets of relationships can generate some simple behavioral patterns, whereas chaotic behavior, in the sense of deterministic chaos, is the result of a relatively small number of non-linear interactions.
[src:complex-systems/complex-system] Therefore, the main difference between chaotic systems and complex systems is their history.
[src:complex-systems/complex-system] Chaotic systems do not rely on their history as complex ones do.
[src:complex-systems/complex-system] Chaotic behavior pushes a system in equilibrium into chaotic order, which means, in other words, out of what we traditionally define as 'order'.
[src:complex-systems/complex-system] On the other hand, complex systems evolve far from equilibrium at the edge of chaos.
[src:complex-systems/complex-system] They evolve at a critical state built up by a history of irreversible and unexpected events, which physicist Murray Gell-Mann called "an accumulation of frozen accidents".
[src:complex-systems/complex-system] In a sense chaotic systems can be regarded as a subset of complex systems distinguished precisely by this absence of historical dependence.
[src:complex-systems/complex-system] Many real complex systems are, in practice and over long but finite periods, robust.
[src:complex-systems/complex-system] However, they do possess the potential for radical qualitative change of kind whilst retaining systemic integrity.
[src:complex-systems/complex-system] Metamorphosis serves as perhaps more than a metaphor for such transformations.
[src:complex-systems/complex-system] A complex system is usually composed of many components and their interactions.
[src:complex-systems/complex-system] Such a system can be represented by a network where nodes represent the components and links represent their interactions.
[src:complex-systems/complex-system] For example, the Internet can be represented as a network composed of nodes (computers) and links (direct connections between computers).
[src:complex-systems/complex-system] Other examples of complex networks include social networks, financial institution interdependencies, airline networks, and biological networks.
[src:complex-systems/nonlinear-system] In mathematics and science, a **nonlinear system** (or a **non-linear system**) is a system in which the change of the output is not proportional to the change of the input.
[src:complex-systems/nonlinear-system] Nonlinear problems are of interest to engineers, biologists, physicists, mathematicians, and many other scientists since most systems are inherently nonlinear in nature.
[src:complex-systems/nonlinear-system] Nonlinear dynamical systems, describing changes in variables over time, may appear chaotic, unpredictable, or counterintuitive, contrasting with much simpler linear systems.
[src:complex-systems/nonlinear-system] In other words, in a nonlinear system of equations, the equation(s) to be solved cannot be written as a linear combination of the unknown variables or functions that appear in them.
[src:complex-systems/nonlinear-system] Systems can be defined as nonlinear, regardless of whether known linear functions appear in the equations.
[src:complex-systems/nonlinear-system] In particular, a differential equation is *linear* if it is linear in terms of the unknown function and its derivatives, even if nonlinear in terms of the other variables appearing in it.
[src:complex-systems/nonlinear-system] As nonlinear dynamical equations are difficult to solve, nonlinear systems are commonly approximated by linear equations (linearization).
[src:complex-systems/nonlinear-system] This works well up to some accuracy and some range for the input values, but some interesting phenomena such as solitons, chaos, and singularities are hidden by linearization.
[src:complex-systems/nonlinear-system] It follows that some aspects of the dynamic behavior of a nonlinear system can appear to be counterintuitive, unpredictable or even chaotic.
[src:complex-systems/nonlinear-system] Although such chaotic behavior may resemble random behavior, it is in fact not random.
[src:complex-systems/nonlinear-system] For example, some aspects of the weather are seen to be chaotic, where simple changes in one part of the system produce complex effects throughout.
[src:complex-systems/nonlinear-system] This nonlinearity is one of the reasons why accurate long-term forecasts are impossible with current technology.
[src:complex-systems/nonlinear-system] Some authors use the term **nonlinear science** for the study of nonlinear systems.
[src:complex-systems/nonlinear-system] Additivity implies homogeneity for any rational *α*, and, for continuous functions, for any real *α*.
[src:complex-systems/nonlinear-system] For a complex *α*, homogeneity does not follow from additivity.
[src:complex-systems/nonlinear-system] For example, an antilinear map is additive but not homogeneous.
[src:complex-systems/nonlinear-system] is called **linear** if $f(x)$ is a linear map (as defined above) and **nonlinear** otherwise.
[src:complex-systems/nonlinear-system] The equation is called *homogeneous* if $C=0$ and $f(x)$ is a homogeneous function.
[src:complex-systems/nonlinear-system] The definition $f(x)=C$ is very general in that x can be any sensible mathematical object (number, vector, function, etc.), and the function $f(x)$ can literally be any mapping, including integration or differentiation with associated constraints (such as boundary values).
[src:complex-systems/nonlinear-system] If $f(x)$ contains differentiation with respect to x , the result will be a differential equation.
[src:complex-systems/nonlinear-system] A nonlinear system of equations consists of a set of equations in several variables such that at least one of them is not a linear equation.
[src:complex-systems/nonlinear-system] For a single equation of the form $f(x)=0,$ many methods have been designed; see Root-finding algorithm.
[src:complex-systems/nonlinear-system] In the case where f is a polynomial, one has a *polynomial equation* such as $x^{2}+x-1=0.$ The general root-finding algorithms apply to polynomial roots, but, generally they do not find all the roots, and when they fail to find a root, this does not imply that there is no roots.
[src:complex-systems/nonlinear-system] Specific methods for polynomials allow finding all roots or the real roots; see real-root isolation.
[src:complex-systems/nonlinear-system] Solving systems of polynomial equations, that is finding the common zeros of a set of several polynomials in several variables is a difficult problem for which elaborate algorithms have been designed, such as Gröbner base algorithms.
[src:complex-systems/nonlinear-system] For the general case of system of equations formed by equating to zero several differentiable functions, the main method is Newton's method and its variants.
[src:complex-systems/nonlinear-system] Generally they may provide a solution, but do not provide any information on the number of solutions.
[src:complex-systems/nonlinear-system] A nonlinear recurrence relation defines successive terms of a sequence as a nonlinear function of preceding terms.
[src:complex-systems/nonlinear-system] Examples of nonlinear recurrence relations are the logistic map and the relations that define the various Hofstadter sequences.
[src:complex-systems/nonlinear-system] Nonlinear discrete models that represent a wide class of nonlinear recurrence relationships include the NARMAX (Nonlinear Autoregressive Moving Average with eXogenous inputs) model and the related nonlinear system identification and analysis procedures.
[src:complex-systems/nonlinear-system] These approaches can be used to study a wide class of complex nonlinear behaviors in the time, frequency, and spatio-temporal domains.
[src:complex-systems/nonlinear-system] A system of differential equations is said to be nonlinear if it is not a system of linear equations.
[src:complex-systems/nonlinear-system] Problems involving nonlinear differential equations are extremely diverse, and methods of solution or analysis are problem dependent.
[src:complex-systems/nonlinear-system] Examples of nonlinear differential equations are the Navier–Stokes equations in fluid dynamics and the Lotka–Volterra equations in biology.
[src:complex-systems/nonlinear-system] One of the greatest difficulties of nonlinear problems is that it is not generally possible to combine known solutions into new solutions.
[src:complex-systems/nonlinear-system] In linear problems, for example, a family of linearly independent solutions can be used to construct general solutions through the superposition principle.
[src:complex-systems/nonlinear-system] A good example of this is one-dimensional heat transport with Dirichlet boundary conditions, the solution of which can be written as a time-dependent linear combination of sinusoids of differing frequencies; this makes solutions very flexible.
[src:complex-systems/nonlinear-system] It is often possible to find several very specific solutions to nonlinear equations, however the lack of a superposition principle prevents the construction of new solutions.
[src:complex-systems/nonlinear-system] First order ordinary differential equations are often exactly solvable by separation of variables, especially for autonomous equations.
[src:complex-systems/nonlinear-system] has $u={\frac {1}{x+C}}$ as a general solution (and also the special solution $u=0,$ corresponding to the limit of the general solution when *C* tends to infinity).
[src:complex-systems/nonlinear-system] and the left-hand side of the equation is not a linear function of u and its derivatives.
[src:complex-systems/nonlinear-system] Note that if the $u^{2}$ term were replaced with u , the problem would be linear (the exponential decay problem).
[src:complex-systems/nonlinear-system] Second and higher order ordinary differential equations (more generally, systems of nonlinear equations) rarely yield closed-form solutions, though implicit solutions and solutions involving nonelementary integrals are encountered.
[src:complex-systems/nonlinear-system] The most common basic approach to studying nonlinear partial differential equations is to change the variables (or otherwise transform the problem) so that the resulting problem is simpler (possibly linear).
[src:complex-systems/nonlinear-system] Sometimes, the equation may be transformed into one or more ordinary differential equations, as seen in separation of variables, which is always useful whether or not the resulting ordinary differential equation(s) is solvable.
[src:complex-systems/nonlinear-system] Another common (though less mathematical) tactic, often exploited in fluid and heat mechanics, is to use scale analysis to simplify a general, natural equation in a certain specific boundary value problem.
[src:complex-systems/nonlinear-system] Other methods include examining the characteristics and using the methods outlined above for ordinary differential equations.
[src:complex-systems/nonlinear-system] A classic, extensively studied nonlinear problem is the dynamics of a frictionless pendulum under the influence of gravity.
[src:complex-systems/nonlinear-system] where gravity points "downwards" and $\theta$ is the angle the pendulum forms with its rest position, as shown in the figure at right.
[src:complex-systems/nonlinear-system] which is an implicit solution involving an elliptic integral.
[src:complex-systems/nonlinear-system] This "solution" generally does not have many uses because most of the nature of the solution is hidden in the nonelementary integral (nonelementary unless $C_{0}=2$ ).
[src:complex-systems/nonlinear-system] Another way to approach the problem is to linearize any nonlinearity (the sine function term in this case) at the various points of interest through Taylor expansions.
[src:complex-systems/nonlinear-system] since $\sin(\theta )\approx \theta$ for $\theta \approx 0$ .
[src:complex-systems/nonlinear-system] This is a simple harmonic oscillator corresponding to oscillations of the pendulum near the bottom of its path.
[src:complex-systems/nonlinear-system] since $\sin(\theta )\approx \pi -\theta$ for $\theta \approx \pi$ .
[src:complex-systems/nonlinear-system] The solution to this problem involves hyperbolic sinusoids, and note that unlike the small angle approximation, this approximation is unstable, meaning that $|\theta |$ will usually grow without limit, though bounded solutions are possible.
[src:complex-systems/nonlinear-system] This corresponds to the difficulty of balancing a pendulum upright, it is literally an unstable state.
[src:complex-systems/nonlinear-system] This corresponds to a free fall problem.
[src:complex-systems/nonlinear-system] A very useful qualitative picture of the pendulum's dynamics may be obtained by piecing together such linearizations, as seen in the figure at right.
[src:complex-systems/nonlinear-system] Other techniques may be used to find (exact) phase portraits and approximate periods.
[src:complex-systems/percolation-theory] In statistical physics and mathematics, **percolation theory** describes the behavior of a network when nodes or links are added.
[src:complex-systems/percolation-theory] This is a geometric type of phase transition, since at a critical fraction of addition the network of small, disconnected clusters merge into significantly larger connected, so-called spanning clusters.
[src:complex-systems/percolation-theory] A representative question (and the source of the name) is as follows.
[src:complex-systems/percolation-theory] Assume that some liquid is poured on top of some porous material.
[src:complex-systems/percolation-theory] Will the liquid be able to make its way from hole to hole and reach the bottom?
[src:complex-systems/percolation-theory] Therefore, for a given *p*, what is the probability that an open path (meaning a path, each of whose links is an "open" bond) exists from the top to the bottom?
[src:complex-systems/percolation-theory] The behavior for large *n* is of primary interest.
[src:complex-systems/percolation-theory] This problem, called now **bond percolation**, was introduced in the mathematics literature by Broadbent & Hammersley (1957), and has been studied intensively by mathematicians and physicists since then.
[src:complex-systems/percolation-theory] In a slightly different mathematical model for obtaining a random graph, a site is "occupied" with probability *p* or "empty" (in which case its edges are removed) with probability 1 – *p*; the corresponding problem is called **site percolation**.
[src:complex-systems/percolation-theory] The question is the same: for a given *p*, what is the probability that a path exists between top and bottom?
[src:complex-systems/percolation-theory] Similarly, one can ask, given a connected graph at what fraction 1 – *p* of failures the graph will become disconnected (no large component).
[src:complex-systems/percolation-theory] The same questions can be asked for any lattice dimension.
[src:complex-systems/percolation-theory] As is quite typical, it is actually easier to examine infinite networks than just large ones.
[src:complex-systems/percolation-theory] In this case the corresponding question is: does an infinite open cluster exist?
[src:complex-systems/percolation-theory] That is, is there a path of connected points of infinite length "through" the network?
[src:complex-systems/percolation-theory] By Kolmogorov's zero–one law, for any given *p*, the probability that an infinite cluster exists is either zero or one.
[src:complex-systems/percolation-theory] Since this probability is an increasing function of *p* (proof via coupling argument), there must be a **critical** *p* (denoted by *p*c) below which the probability is always 0 and above which the probability is always 1.
[src:complex-systems/percolation-theory] In practice, this criticality is very easy to observe.
[src:complex-systems/percolation-theory] Even for *n* as small as 100, the probability of an open path from the top to the bottom increases sharply from very close to zero to very close to one in a short span of values of *p*.
[src:complex-systems/percolation-theory] The Flory–Stockmayer theory (1941), which studied the transition to gelation in polymerization reactions, was the first theory investigating percolation processes.
[src:complex-systems/percolation-theory] The history of the percolation model as we know it has its root in the coal industry.
[src:complex-systems/percolation-theory] Since the industrial revolution, the economical importance of this source of energy fostered many scientific studies to understand its composition and optimize its use.
[src:complex-systems/percolation-theory] During the 1930s and 1940s, the qualitative analysis by organic chemistry left more and more room to more quantitative studies.
[src:complex-systems/percolation-theory] In this context, the British Coal Utilisation Research Association (BCURA) was created in 1938.
[src:complex-systems/percolation-theory] It was a research association funded by the coal mines owners.
[src:complex-systems/percolation-theory] In 1942, Rosalind Franklin, who then recently graduated in chemistry from the university of Cambridge, joined the BCURA.
[src:complex-systems/percolation-theory] She started research on the density and porosity of coal.
[src:complex-systems/percolation-theory] During the Second World War, coal was an important strategic resource.
[src:complex-systems/percolation-theory] It was used as a source of energy, but also was the main constituent of gas masks.
[src:complex-systems/percolation-theory] To measure its 'real' density, one was to sink it in a liquid or a gas whose molecules are small enough to fill its microscopic pores.
[src:complex-systems/percolation-theory] She also discovered that the size of these structures depends on the temperature of carbonation during the coal production.
[src:complex-systems/percolation-theory] With this research, she obtained a PhD degree and left the BCURA in 1946.
[src:complex-systems/percolation-theory] In the mid fifties, Simon Broadbent worked in the BCURA as a statistician.
[src:complex-systems/percolation-theory] Among other interests, he studied the use of coal in gas masks.
[src:complex-systems/percolation-theory] One question is to understand how a fluid can diffuse in the coal pores, modeled as a random maze of open or closed tunnels.
[src:complex-systems/percolation-theory] In 1954, during a symposium on Monte Carlo methods, he asks questions to John Hammersley on the use of numerical methods to analyze this model.
[src:complex-systems/percolation-theory] Broadbent and Hammersley introduced in their article of 1957 a mathematical model to model this phenomenon, that is percolation.
[src:complex-systems/percolation-theory] For most infinite lattice graphs, *p*c cannot be calculated exactly, though in some cases there is an exact value.
[src:complex-systems/percolation-theory] This indicates that for a given degree distribution, the clustering leads to a larger percolation threshold, mainly because for a fixed number of links, the clustering structure reinforces the core of the network with the price of diluting the global connections.
[src:complex-systems/percolation-theory] For networks with high clustering, strong clustering could induce the core–periphery structure, in which the core and periphery might percolate at different critical points, and the above approximate treatment is not applicable.
[src:complex-systems/percolation-theory] The main fact in the subcritical phase is "exponential decay".
[src:complex-systems/percolation-theory] That is, when *p* < *p*c, the probability that a specific point (for example, the origin) is contained in an open cluster (meaning a maximal connected set of "open" edges of the graph) of size *r* decays to zero exponentially in *r*.
[src:complex-systems/percolation-theory] This was proved for percolation in three and more dimensions by Menshikov (1986) and independently by Aizenman & Barsky (1987).
[src:complex-systems/percolation-theory] In two dimensions, it formed part of Kesten's proof that *p*c = ⁠1/2⁠.
[src:complex-systems/percolation-theory] The dual graph of the square lattice **ℤ**2 is also the square lattice.
[src:complex-systems/percolation-theory] It follows that, in two dimensions, the supercritical phase is dual to a subcritical percolation process.
[src:complex-systems/percolation-theory] This provides essentially full information about the supercritical model with *d* = 2.
[src:complex-systems/percolation-theory] The main result for the supercritical phase in three and more dimensions is that, for sufficiently large *N*, there is almost certainly an infinite open cluster in the two-dimensional slab **ℤ**2 × [0, *N*]*d* − 2.
[src:complex-systems/percolation-theory] This was proved by Grimmett & Marstrand (1990).
[src:complex-systems/percolation-theory] In two dimensions with *p* < ⁠1/2⁠, there is with probability one a unique infinite closed cluster (a closed cluster is a maximal connected set of "closed" edges of the graph).
[src:complex-systems/percolation-theory] Thus the subcritical phase may be described as finite open islands in an infinite closed ocean.
[src:complex-systems/percolation-theory] When *p* > ⁠1/2⁠ just the opposite occurs, with finite closed islands in an infinite open ocean.
[src:complex-systems/percolation-theory] The picture is more complicated when *d* ≥ 3 since *p*c < ⁠1/2⁠, and there is coexistence of infinite open and closed clusters for *p* between *p*c and 1 − *p*c.
[src:complex-systems/percolation-theory] Percolation has a singularity at the critical point *p* = *p*c and many properties behave as of a power-law with $p-p_{c}$ , near $p_{c}$ .
[src:complex-systems/percolation-theory] Scaling theory predicts the existence of critical exponents, depending on the number *d* of dimensions, that determine the class of the singularity.
[src:complex-systems/percolation-theory] When *d* = 2 these predictions are backed up by arguments from conformal field theory and Schramm–Loewner evolution, and include predicted numerical values for the exponents.
[src:complex-systems/percolation-theory] Most of these predictions are conjectural except when the number *d* of dimensions satisfies either *d* = 2 or *d* ≥ 6.
[src:complex-systems/percolation-theory] In 11 or more dimensions, these facts are largely proved using a technique known as the lace expansion.
[src:complex-systems/percolation-theory] It is believed that a version of the lace expansion should be valid for 7 or more dimensions, perhaps with implications also for the threshold case of 6 dimensions.
[src:complex-systems/percolation-theory] The connection of percolation to the lace expansion is found in Hara & Slade (1990).
[src:complex-systems/percolation-theory] In two dimensions, the first fact ("no percolation in the critical phase") is proved for many lattices, using duality.
[src:complex-systems/percolation-theory] Substantial progress has been made on two-dimensional percolation through the conjecture of Oded Schramm that the scaling limit of a large cluster may be described in terms of a Schramm–Loewner evolution.
[src:complex-systems/percolation-theory] This conjecture was proved by Smirnov (2001) in the special case of site percolation on the triangular lattice.
[src:complex-systems/percolation-theory] Percolation theory has been used to successfully predict the fragmentation of biological virus shells (capsids), with the fragmentation threshold of Hepatitis B virus capsid predicted and detected experimentally.
[src:complex-systems/percolation-theory] When a critical number of subunits has been randomly removed from the nanoscopic shell, it fragments and this fragmentation may be detected using Charge Detection Mass Spectroscopy (CDMS) among other single-particle techniques.
[src:complex-systems/percolation-theory] This is a molecular analog to the common board game Jenga, and has relevance to the broader study of virus disassembly.
[src:complex-systems/percolation-theory] More stable viral particles (tilings with greater fragmentation thresholds) are found in greater abundance in nature.
[src:complex-systems/percolation-theory] Percolation theory has been applied to studies of how environment fragmentation impacts animal habitats and models of how the plague bacterium *Yersinia pestis* spreads.
[src:complex-systems/phase-transition] In physics, chemistry and biology, a **phase transition** (or **phase change**) is the physical process of transition between one state of a medium and another.
[src:complex-systems/phase-transition] Commonly the term is used to refer to changes among the basic states of matter: solid, liquid, and gas, and in rare cases, plasma.
[src:complex-systems/phase-transition] A phase of a thermodynamic system and the states of matter have uniform physical properties.
[src:complex-systems/phase-transition] During a phase transition of a given medium, certain properties of the medium change as a result of the change of external conditions, such as temperature or pressure.
[src:complex-systems/phase-transition] This can be a discontinuous change; for example, a liquid may become gas upon heating to its boiling point, resulting in an abrupt change in volume.
[src:complex-systems/phase-transition] The identification of the external conditions at which a transformation occurs defines the phase transition point.
[src:complex-systems/phase-transition] Phase transitions commonly refer to when a substance transforms between one of the four states of matter to another.
[src:complex-systems/phase-transition] At the phase transition point for a substance, for instance the boiling point, the two phases involved - liquid and vapor, have identical free energies and therefore are equally likely to exist.
[src:complex-systems/phase-transition] Below the boiling point, the liquid is the more stable state of the two, whereas above the boiling point the gaseous form is the more stable.
[src:complex-systems/phase-transition] For a single component, the most stable phase at different temperatures and pressures can be shown on a phase diagram.
[src:complex-systems/phase-transition] Such a diagram usually depicts states in equilibrium.
[src:complex-systems/phase-transition] A phase transition usually occurs when the pressure or temperature changes and the system crosses from one region to another, like water turning from liquid to solid as soon as the temperature drops below the freezing point.
[src:complex-systems/phase-transition] In exception to the usual case, it is sometimes possible to change the state of a system diabatically (as opposed to adiabatically) in such a way that it can be brought past a phase transition point without undergoing a phase transition.
[src:complex-systems/phase-transition] The resulting state is metastable, i.e., less stable than the phase to which the transition would have occurred, but not unstable either.
[src:complex-systems/phase-transition] This occurs in superheating and supercooling, for example.
[src:complex-systems/phase-transition] Metastable states do not appear on usual phase diagrams.
[src:complex-systems/phase-transition] Phase transitions can also occur when a solid changes to a different structure without changing its chemical makeup.
[src:complex-systems/phase-transition] In elements, this is known as allotropy, whereas in compounds it is known as polymorphism.
[src:complex-systems/phase-transition] The change from one crystal structure to another, from a crystalline solid to an amorphous solid, or from one amorphous structure to another (polyamorphs) are all examples of solid to solid phase transitions.
[src:complex-systems/phase-transition] The martensitic transformation occurs as one of the many phase transformations in carbon steel and stands as a model for displacive phase transformations.
[src:complex-systems/phase-transition] Order-disorder transitions such as in alpha-titanium aluminides.
[src:complex-systems/phase-transition] As with states of matter, there is also a metastable to equilibrium phase transformation for structural phase transitions.
[src:complex-systems/phase-transition] A metastable polymorph which forms rapidly due to lower surface energy will transform to an equilibrium phase given sufficient thermal input to overcome an energetic barrier.
[src:complex-systems/phase-transition] Many dynamic, or soft, microporous materials exhibit structural phase transitions between closed and open forms.
[src:complex-systems/phase-transition] Metal–organic frameworks, in particular, have been extensively studied for this behavior.
[src:complex-systems/phase-transition] The phase landscape can be more complex, with intermediate phases discovered.
[src:complex-systems/phase-transition] Further examples show that guest molecules can stabilize specific phases, resulting in crystal configurations that depend on the composition of the surrounding atmosphere.
[src:complex-systems/phase-transition] Phase transitions can also describe the change between different kinds of magnetic ordering.
[src:complex-systems/phase-transition] The most well-known is the transition between the ferromagnetic and paramagnetic phases of magnetic materials, which occurs at what is called the Curie point.
[src:complex-systems/phase-transition] Another example is the transition between differently ordered, commensurate or incommensurate, magnetic structures, such as in cerium antimonide.
[src:complex-systems/phase-transition] A simplified but highly useful model of magnetic phase transitions is provided by the Ising model.
[src:complex-systems/phase-transition] Phase transitions involving solutions and mixtures are more complicated than transitions involving a single compound.
[src:complex-systems/phase-transition] This is often the case in solid solutions, where the two components are isostructural.
[src:complex-systems/phase-transition] There are also a number of phase transitions involving three phases: a eutectic transformation, in which a two-component single-phase liquid is cooled and transforms into two solid phases.
[src:complex-systems/phase-transition] The same process, but beginning with a solid instead of a liquid is called a eutectoid transformation.
[src:complex-systems/phase-transition] A peritectic transformation, in which a two-component single-phase solid is heated and transforms into a solid phase and a liquid phase.
[src:complex-systems/phase-transition] A peritectoid reaction is a peritectoid reaction, except involving only solid phases.
[src:complex-systems/phase-transition] A monotectic reaction consists of change from a liquid and to a combination of a solid and a second liquid, where the two liquids display a miscibility gap.
[src:complex-systems/phase-transition] Separation into multiple phases can occur via spinodal decomposition, in which a single phase is cooled and separates into two different compositions.
[src:complex-systems/phase-transition] Non-equilibrium mixtures can occur, such as in supersaturation.
[src:complex-systems/phase-transition] Phase transitions occur when the thermodynamic free energy of a system is non-analytic for some choice of thermodynamic variables (cf. phases).
[src:complex-systems/phase-transition] This condition generally stems from the interactions of a large number of particles in a system, and does not appear in systems that are small.
[src:complex-systems/phase-transition] Phase transitions can occur for non-thermodynamic systems, where temperature is not a parameter.
[src:complex-systems/phase-transition] Examples include: quantum phase transitions, dynamic phase transitions, and topological (structural) phase transitions.
[src:complex-systems/phase-transition] In these types of systems other parameters take the place of temperature.
[src:complex-systems/phase-transition] For instance, connection probability replaces temperature for percolating networks.
[src:complex-systems/phase-transition] Paul Ehrenfest classified phase transitions based on the behavior of the thermodynamic free energy as a function of other thermodynamic variables.
[src:complex-systems/phase-transition] The various solid/liquid/gas transitions are classified as first-order transitions because they involve a discontinuous change in density, which is the (inverse of the) first derivative of the free energy with respect to pressure.
[src:complex-systems/phase-transition] *Second-order phase transitions* are continuous in the first derivative (the order parameter, which is the first derivative of the free energy with respect to the external field, is continuous across the transition) but exhibit discontinuity in a second derivative of the free energy.
[src:complex-systems/phase-transition] Under the Ehrenfest scheme, there could in principle be third, fourth, and higher-order phase transitions, but in practice, only first- and second-order phase transitions are generally observed.
[src:complex-systems/phase-transition] Examples of exceptions to this include the Gross–Witten–Wadia phase transition in 2-D lattice quantum chromodynamics, which is a third-order phase transition, and the Tracy–Widom distribution, which can be interpreted as a third-order transition.
[src:complex-systems/phase-transition] The Curie points of many ferromagnetics are also comsidered third-order transitions, as shown by their specific heat having a sudden change in slope.
[src:complex-systems/phase-transition] The concept of the second-order phase transition, was for a while, controversial, as it seemed to require two "sheets" of the Gibbs free energy to osculate exactly, which was considered so unlikely as to likely never occur.
[src:complex-systems/phase-transition] Cornelis Gorter replied the criticism, pointing out that the Gibbs free energy surface might have two sheets on one side, but only one sheet on the other side, creating a forked appearance.
[src:complex-systems/phase-transition] The first example of a phase transition discovered that did not fit into the Ehrenfest classification was the exact solution of the Ising model, discovered in 1944 by Lars Onsager.
[src:complex-systems/phase-transition] The exact specific heat differed from the earlier mean-field approximations, which had predicted that it has a simple discontinuity at critical temperature; instead, the exact specific heat diverged logarithmically at the critical temperature.
[src:complex-systems/phase-transition] In the following decades, the Ehrenfest classification was replaced by a simplified scheme that is able to incorporate such transitions.
[src:complex-systems/phase-transition] Related primary research reports have suggested that quenched disorder can broaden a first-order transition: that while transformation is completed over a finite range of temperatures, phenomena like supercooling and superheating survive, and hysteresis is observed on thermal cycling.
[src:complex-systems/phase-transition] In contrast to viscosity, thermal expansion and heat capacity of amorphous materials show a relatively sudden change at the glass transition temperature, a change that enables accurate detection using differential scanning calorimetry measurements.
[src:complex-systems/phase-transition] Several transitions are known as *infinite-order phase transitions*.
[src:complex-systems/phase-transition] They are continuous but break no symmetries.
[src:complex-systems/phase-transition] The most famous example is the Kosterlitz–Thouless transition in the two-dimensional XY model.
[src:complex-systems/phase-transition] Many quantum phase transitions, e.g., in two-dimensional electron gases, belong to this class.
[src:complex-systems/phase-transition] Apart from isolated, simple phase transitions, there exist transition lines as well as multicritical points, when varying external parameters like the magnetic field or composition.
[src:complex-systems/phase-transition] The liquid–glass transition is observed in many polymers and other liquids that can be supercooled far below the melting point of the crystalline phase.
[src:complex-systems/phase-transition] It is not a transition between thermodynamic ground states: it is widely believed that the true ground state is always crystalline.
[src:complex-systems/phase-transition] Glass is a *quenched disorder* state, and its entropy, density, and so on, depend on the thermal history.
[src:complex-systems/phase-transition] Therefore, the glass transition is primarily a dynamic phenomenon: on cooling a liquid, internal degrees of freedom successively fall out of equilibrium.
[src:complex-systems/phase-transition] Some theoretical methods predict an underlying phase transition in the hypothetical limit of infinitely long relaxation times.
[src:complex-systems/phase-transition] No direct experimental evidence supports the existence of these transitions.
[src:complex-systems/phase-transition] A disorder-broadened first-order transition occurs over a finite range of temperatures where the fraction of the low-temperature equilibrium phase grows from zero to one (100%) as the temperature is lowered.
[src:complex-systems/phase-transition] This continuous variation of the coexisting fractions with temperature raised interesting possibilities.
[src:complex-systems/phase-transition] On cooling, some liquids vitrify into a glass rather than transform to the equilibrium crystal phase.
[src:complex-systems/phase-transition] This happens if the cooling rate is faster than a critical cooling rate, and is attributed to the molecular motions becoming so slow that the molecules cannot rearrange into the crystal positions.
[src:complex-systems/phase-transition] This slowing down happens below a glass-formation temperature *T*g, which may depend on the applied pressure.
[src:complex-systems/phase-transition] If the first-order freezing transition occurs over a range of temperatures, and *T*g falls within this range, then there is an interesting possibility that the transition is arrested when it is partial and incomplete.
[src:complex-systems/phase-transition] Extending these ideas to first-order magnetic transitions being arrested at low temperatures, resulted in the observation of incomplete magnetic transitions, with two magnetic phases coexisting, down to the lowest temperature.
[src:complex-systems/phase-transition] First reported in the case of a ferromagnetic to anti-ferromagnetic transition, such persistent phase coexistence has now been reported across a variety of first-order magnetic transitions.
[src:complex-systems/phase-transition] These include colossal-magnetoresistance manganite materials, magnetocaloric materials, magnetic shape memory materials, and other materials.
[src:complex-systems/phase-transition] The interesting feature of these observations of *T*g falling within the temperature range over which the transition occurs is that the first-order magnetic transition is influenced by magnetic field, just like the structural transition is influenced by pressure.
[src:complex-systems/phase-transition] The relative ease with which magnetic fields can be controlled, in contrast to pressure, raises the possibility that one can study the interplay between *T*g and *T*c in an exhaustive way.
[src:complex-systems/phase-transition] Phase coexistence across first-order magnetic transitions will then enable the resolution of outstanding issues in understanding glasses.
[src:complex-systems/phase-transition] In any system containing liquid and gaseous phases, there exists a special combination of pressure and temperature, known as the critical point, at which the transition between liquid and gas becomes a second-order transition.
[src:complex-systems/phase-transition] Near the critical point, the fluid is sufficiently hot and compressed that the distinction between the liquid and gaseous phases is almost non-existent.
[src:complex-systems/phase-transition] This is associated with the phenomenon of critical opalescence, a milky appearance of the liquid due to density fluctuations at all possible wavelengths (including those of visible light).
[src:complex-systems/phase-transition] Phase transitions often involve a symmetry breaking process.
[src:complex-systems/phase-transition] For instance, the cooling of a fluid into a crystalline solid breaks continuous translation symmetry: each point in the fluid has the same properties, but each point in a crystal does not have the same properties (unless the points are chosen from the lattice points of the crystal lattice).
[src:complex-systems/phase-transition] Typically, the high-temperature phase contains more symmetries than the low-temperature phase due to spontaneous symmetry breaking, with the exception of certain accidental symmetries (e.g. the formation of heavy virtual particles, which only occurs at low temperatures).
[src:complex-systems/phase-transition] An **order parameter** is a measure of the degree of order across the boundaries in a phase transition system; it normally takes on the value of zero in one phase (usually above the critical point) and nonzero in the other.
[src:complex-systems/phase-transition] At the critical point, the order parameter susceptibility (the change of an extensive property under variation of an intensive property) will usually diverge.
[src:complex-systems/phase-transition] An example of an order parameter is the net magnetization in a ferromagnetic system undergoing a phase transition.
[src:complex-systems/phase-transition] For liquid/gas transitions, the order parameter is the difference of the densities.
[src:complex-systems/phase-transition] From a theoretical perspective, order parameters arise from symmetry breaking.
[src:complex-systems/phase-transition] When this happens, one needs to introduce one or more extra variables to describe the state of the system.
[src:complex-systems/phase-transition] For example, in the ferromagnetic phase, one must provide the net magnetization, whose direction was spontaneously chosen when the system cooled below the Curie point.
[src:complex-systems/phase-transition] However, note that order parameters can also be defined for non-symmetry-breaking transitions.
[src:complex-systems/phase-transition] Some phase transitions, such as superconducting and ferromagnetic, can have order parameters for more than one degree of freedom.
[src:complex-systems/phase-transition] In such phases, the order parameter may take the form of a complex number, a vector, or even a tensor, the magnitude of which goes to zero at the phase transition.
[src:complex-systems/phase-transition] There also exist dual descriptions of phase transitions in terms of disorder parameters.
[src:complex-systems/phase-transition] These indicate the presence of line-like excitations such as vortex- or defect lines.
[src:complex-systems/phase-transition] Symmetry-breaking phase transitions play an important role in cosmology.
[src:complex-systems/phase-transition] As the universe expanded and cooled, the vacuum underwent a series of symmetry-breaking phase transitions.
[src:complex-systems/phase-transition] For example, the electroweak transition broke the SU(2)×U(1) symmetry of the electroweak field into the U(1) symmetry of the present-day electromagnetic field.
[src:complex-systems/phase-transition] This transition is important to explain the asymmetry between the amount of matter and antimatter in the present-day universe, according to electroweak baryogenesis theory.
[src:complex-systems/phase-transition] Progressive phase transitions in an expanding universe are implicated in the development of order in the universe, as is illustrated by the work of Eric Chaisson and David Layzer.
[src:complex-systems/phase-transition] See also relational order theories and order and disorder.
[src:complex-systems/phase-transition] Continuous phase transitions are easier to study than first-order transitions due to the absence of latent heat, and they have been discovered to have many interesting properties.
[src:complex-systems/phase-transition] The phenomena associated with continuous phase transitions are called critical phenomena, due to their association with critical points.
[src:complex-systems/phase-transition] Continuous phase transitions can be characterized by parameters known as critical exponents.
[src:complex-systems/phase-transition] The most important one is perhaps the exponent describing the divergence of the thermal correlation length by approaching the transition.
[src:complex-systems/phase-transition] For instance, let us examine the behavior of the heat capacity near such a transition.
[src:complex-systems/phase-transition] We vary the temperature *T* of the system while keeping all the other thermodynamic variables fixed and find that the transition occurs at some critical temperature *T*c.
[src:complex-systems/phase-transition] The heat capacity of amorphous materials has such a behaviour near the glass transition temperature where the universal critical exponent *α* = 0.59 A similar behavior, but with the exponent *ν* instead of *α*, applies for the correlation length.
[src:complex-systems/phase-transition] The critical exponents are not necessarily the same above and below the critical temperature.
[src:complex-systems/phase-transition] When a continuous symmetry is explicitly broken down to a discrete symmetry by irrelevant (in the renormalization group sense) anisotropies, then some exponents (such as $\gamma$ , the exponent of the susceptibility) are not identical.
[src:complex-systems/phase-transition] For $\alpha <-1$ , the heat capacity remains differentiable at the transition temperature, although discontinuities appear at higher-order derivatives.
[src:complex-systems/phase-transition] For $-1\leq \alpha <0$ , the heat capacity has a "kink" at the transition temperature.
[src:complex-systems/phase-transition] This is the behavior of liquid helium at the lambda transition from a normal state to the superfluid state, for which experiments have found *α* = −0.013 ± 0.003.
[src:complex-systems/phase-transition] At least one experiment was performed in the zero-gravity conditions of an orbiting satellite to minimize pressure differences in the sample.
[src:complex-systems/phase-transition] This experimental value of α agrees with theoretical predictions based on variational perturbation theory.
[src:complex-systems/phase-transition] For 0 < *α* < 1, the heat capacity diverges at the transition temperature (though, since *α* < 1, the enthalpy stays finite).
[src:complex-systems/phase-transition] An example of such behavior is the 3D ferromagnetic phase transition.
[src:complex-systems/phase-transition] In the three-dimensional Ising model for uniaxial magnets, detailed theoretical studies have yielded the exponent *α* ≈ +0.110.
[src:complex-systems/phase-transition] Some model systems do not obey a power-law behavior.
[src:complex-systems/phase-transition] For example, mean field theory predicts a finite discontinuity of the heat capacity at the transition temperature, and the two-dimensional Ising model has a logarithmic divergence.
[src:complex-systems/phase-transition] However, these systems are limiting cases and an exception to the rule.
[src:complex-systems/phase-transition] Real phase transitions exhibit power-law behavior.
[src:complex-systems/phase-transition] Several other critical exponents, *β*, *γ*, *δ*, *ν*, and *η*, are defined, examining the power law behavior of a measurable physical quantity near the phase transition.
[src:complex-systems/phase-transition] It can be shown that there are only two independent exponents, e.g.
[src:complex-systems/phase-transition] It is a remarkable fact that phase transitions arising in different systems often possess the same set of critical exponents.
[src:complex-systems/phase-transition] This phenomenon is known as *universality*.
[src:complex-systems/phase-transition] For example, the critical exponents at the liquid–gas critical point have been found to be independent of the chemical composition of the fluid.
[src:complex-systems/phase-transition] More impressively, but understandably from above, they are an exact match for the critical exponents of the ferromagnetic phase transition in uniaxial magnets.
[src:complex-systems/phase-transition] Such systems are said to be in the same universality class.
[src:complex-systems/phase-transition] Again, the divergence of the correlation length is the essential point.
[src:complex-systems/phase-transition] There are also other critical phenomena; e.g., besides *static functions* there is also *critical dynamics*.
[src:complex-systems/phase-transition] As a consequence, at a phase transition one may observe *critical slowing down* or *speeding up*.
[src:complex-systems/phase-transition] Connected to the previous phenomenon is also the phenomenon of *enhanced fluctuations* before the phase transition, as a consequence of lower degree of stability of the initial phase of the system.
[src:complex-systems/phase-transition] The large *static universality classes* of a continuous phase transition split into smaller *dynamic universality* classes.
[src:complex-systems/phase-transition] In addition to the critical exponents, there are also universal relations for certain static or dynamic functions of the magnetic fields and temperature differences from the critical value.
[src:complex-systems/phase-transition] A variety of methods are applied for studying the various effects.
[src:complex-systems/phase-transition] Phase transitions play many important roles in biological systems.
[src:complex-systems/phase-transition] In *biological membranes*, gel to liquid crystalline phase transitions play a critical role in physiological functioning of biomembranes.
[src:complex-systems/phase-transition] In gel phase, due to low fluidity of membrane lipid fatty-acyl chains, membrane proteins have restricted movement and thus are restrained in exercise of their physiological role.
[src:complex-systems/phase-transition] Plants depend critically on photosynthesis by chloroplast thylakoid membranes which are exposed cold environmental temperatures.
[src:complex-systems/phase-transition] Thylakoid membranes retain innate fluidity even at relatively low temperatures because of high degree of fatty-acyl disorder allowed by their high content of linolenic acid, 18-carbon chain with 3-double bonds.
[src:complex-systems/phase-transition] Gel-to-liquid crystalline phase transition temperature of biological membranes can be determined by many techniques including calorimetry, fluorescence, spin label electron paramagnetic resonance and NMR by recording measurements of the concerned parameter by at series of sample temperatures.
[src:complex-systems/phase-transition] A simple method for its determination from 13-C NMR line intensities has also been proposed.
[src:complex-systems/phase-transition] It has been proposed that some biological systems might lie near critical points.
[src:complex-systems/phase-transition] Examples include neural networks in the salamander retina, bird flocks, gene expression networks in Drosophila, and protein folding.
[src:complex-systems/phase-transition] However, it is not clear whether or not alternative reasons could explain some of the phenomena supporting arguments for criticality.
[src:complex-systems/phase-transition] It has also been suggested that biological organisms share two key properties of phase transitions: the change of macroscopic behavior and the coherence of a system at a critical point.
[src:complex-systems/phase-transition] Phase transitions are prominent feature of motor behavior in biological systems.
[src:complex-systems/phase-transition] Spontaneous gait transitions, as well as fatigue-induced motor task disengagements, show typical critical behavior as an intimation of the sudden qualitative change of the previously stable motor behavioral pattern.
[src:complex-systems/phase-transition] The characteristic feature of second order phase transitions is the appearance of fractals in some scale-free properties.
[src:complex-systems/phase-transition] It has long been known that protein globules are shaped by interactions with water.
[src:complex-systems/phase-transition] There are 20 amino acids that form side groups on protein peptide chains range from hydrophilic to hydrophobic, causing the former to lie near the globular surface, while the latter lie closer to the globular center.
[src:complex-systems/phase-transition] Twenty fractals were discovered in solvent associated surface areas of > 5000 protein segments.
[src:complex-systems/phase-transition] The existence of these fractals proves that proteins function near critical points of second-order phase transitions.
[src:complex-systems/phase-transition] In groups of organisms in stress (when approaching critical transitions), correlations tend to increase, while at the same time, fluctuations also increase.
[src:complex-systems/phase-transition] This effect is supported by many experiments and observations of groups of people, mice, trees, and grassy plants.
[src:complex-systems/phase-transition] Phase transitions have been hypothesised to occur in social systems viewed as dynamical systems.
[src:complex-systems/phase-transition] A hypothesis proposed in the 1990s and 2000s in the context of peace and armed conflict is that when a conflict that is non-violent shifts to a phase of armed conflict, this is a phase transition from latent to manifest phases within the dynamical system.
[src:complex-systems/power-law] In statistics, a **power law** is a functional relationship between two quantities, where a relative change in one quantity results in a relative change in the other quantity proportional to the change raised to a constant exponent: one quantity varies as a power of another.
[src:complex-systems/power-law] The change is independent of the initial size of those quantities.
[src:complex-systems/power-law] For instance, the area of a square has a power law relationship with the length of its side, since if the length is doubled, the area is multiplied by 22, while if the length is tripled, the area is multiplied by 32, and so on.
[src:complex-systems/power-law] Empirical distributions can only fit a power law for a limited range of values, because a pure power law would allow for arbitrarily large or small values.
[src:complex-systems/power-law] Acoustic attenuation follows frequency power-laws within wide frequency bands for many complex media.
[src:complex-systems/power-law] Allometric scaling laws for relationships between biological variables are among the best known power-law functions in nature.
[src:complex-systems/power-law] The power-law model does not obey the treasured paradigm of statistical completeness.
[src:complex-systems/power-law] Especially probability bounds, the suspected cause of typical bending and/or flattening phenomena in the high- and low-frequency graphical segments, are parametrically absent in the standard model.
[src:complex-systems/power-law] One attribute of power laws is their scale invariance.
[src:complex-systems/power-law] Given a relation $f(x)=ax^{-k}$ , scaling the argument x by a constant factor c causes only a proportionate scaling of the function itself.
[src:complex-systems/power-law] where $\propto$ denotes direct proportionality.
[src:complex-systems/power-law] That is, scaling by a constant c simply multiplies the original power-law relation by the constant $c^{-k}$ .
[src:complex-systems/power-law] Thus, it follows that all power laws with a particular scaling exponent are equivalent up to constant factors, since each is simply a scaled version of the others.
[src:complex-systems/power-law] This behavior is what produces the linear relationship when logarithms are taken of both $f(x)$ and x , and the straight-line on the log–log plot is often called the *signature* of a power law.
[src:complex-systems/power-law] With real data, such straightness is a necessary, but not sufficient, condition for the data following a power-law relation.
[src:complex-systems/power-law] In fact, there are many ways to generate finite amounts of data that mimic this signature behavior, but, in their asymptotic limit, are not true power laws.
[src:complex-systems/power-law] Thus, accurately fitting and validating power-law models is an active area of research in statistics; see below.
[src:complex-systems/power-law] A power-law $x^{-k}$ has a well-defined mean over $x\in [1,\infty )$ only if $k>2$ , and it has a finite variance only if $k>3$ ; most identified power laws in nature have exponents such that the mean is well-defined but the variance is not, implying they are capable of black swan behavior.
[src:complex-systems/power-law] This is exemplified by the effect, on the mean income, of the inclusion of the person with the highest income in the world into a sample of individuals of otherwise similar income.
[src:complex-systems/power-law] Income is distributed according to a power-law known as the Pareto distribution (for example, the net worth of Americans is distributed according to a power law with an exponent of 2).
[src:complex-systems/power-law] On the one hand, this makes it incorrect to apply traditional statistics that are based on variance and standard deviation (such as regression analysis).
[src:complex-systems/power-law] On the other hand, this also allows for cost-efficient interventions.
[src:complex-systems/power-law] For example, given that car exhaust is distributed according to a power-law among cars (very few cars contribute to most contamination) it would be sufficient to eliminate those very few cars from the road to reduce total exhaust substantially.
[src:complex-systems/power-law] The median does exist, however: for a power law *x* –*k*, with exponent ⁠ $k>1$ ⁠, it takes the value 21/(*k* – 1)*x*min, where *x*min is the minimum value for which the power law holds.
[src:complex-systems/power-law] The equivalence of power laws with a particular scaling exponent can have a deeper origin in the dynamical processes that generate the power-law relation.
[src:complex-systems/power-law] In physics, for example, phase transitions in thermodynamic systems are associated with the emergence of power-law distributions of certain quantities, whose exponents are referred to as the critical exponents of the system.
[src:complex-systems/power-law] Diverse systems with the same critical exponents—that is, which display identical scaling behaviour as they approach criticality—can be shown, via renormalization group theory, to share the same fundamental dynamics.
[src:complex-systems/power-law] For instance, the behavior of water and CO2 at their boiling points fall in the same universality class because they have identical critical exponents.
[src:complex-systems/power-law] In fact, almost all material phase transitions are described by a small set of universality classes.
[src:complex-systems/power-law] Similar observations have been made, though not as comprehensively, for various self-organized critical systems, where the critical point of the system is an attractor.
[src:complex-systems/power-law] Formally, this sharing of dynamics is referred to as universality, and systems with precisely the same critical exponents are said to belong to the same universality class.
[src:complex-systems/power-law] Scientific interest in power-law relations stems partly from the ease with which certain general classes of mechanisms generate them.
[src:complex-systems/power-law] The demonstration of a power-law relation in some data can point to specific kinds of mechanisms that might underlie the natural phenomenon in question, and can indicate a deep connection with other, seemingly unrelated systems; see also universality above.
[src:complex-systems/power-law] The ubiquity of power-law relations in physics is partly due to dimensional constraints, while in complex systems, power laws are often thought to be signatures of hierarchy or of specific stochastic processes.
[src:complex-systems/power-law] A few notable examples of power laws are Pareto's law of income distribution, structural self-similarity of fractals, scaling laws in biological systems, and scaling laws in cities.
[src:complex-systems/power-law] Research on the origins of power-law relations, and efforts to observe and validate them in the real world, is an active topic of research in many fields of science, including physics, computer science, linguistics, geophysics, neuroscience, systematics, sociology, economics and more.
[src:complex-systems/power-law] However, much of the recent interest in power laws comes from the study of probability distributions: The distributions of a wide variety of quantities seem to follow the power-law form, at least in their upper tail (large events).
[src:complex-systems/power-law] The behavior of these large events connects these quantities to the study of theory of large deviations (also called extreme value theory), which considers the frequency of extremely rare events like stock market crashes and large natural disasters.
[src:complex-systems/power-law] It is primarily in the study of statistical distributions that the name "power law" is used.
[src:complex-systems/power-law] More often one uses an asymptotic power law – one that is only true in the limit; see power-law probability distributions below for details.
[src:complex-systems/power-law] Typically the exponent falls in the range $2<\alpha <3$ , though not always.
[src:complex-systems/power-law] More than a hundred power-law distributions have been identified in physics (e.g. sandpile avalanches), biology (e.g. species extinction and body mass), and the social sciences (e.g. city sizes and income).
[src:complex-systems/power-law] A broken power law is a piecewise function, consisting of two or more power laws, combined with a threshold.
[src:complex-systems/power-law] The pieces of a broken power law can be smoothly spliced together to construct a smoothly broken power law.
[src:complex-systems/power-law] There are different possible ways to splice together power laws.
[src:complex-systems/power-law] When the function is plotted as a log-log plot with horizontal axis being $\ln x$ and vertical axis being $\ln(y/y_{0}+a)$ , the plot is composed of $n+1$ linear segments with slopes $c_{0},c_{1},\dots ,c_{n}$ , separated at $x=x_{1},\dots ,x_{n}$ , smoothly spliced together.
[src:complex-systems/power-law] The size of $f_{i}$ determines the sharpness of splicing between segments $i-1,i$ .
[src:complex-systems/power-law] where $\alpha >1$ , and $L(x)$ is a slowly varying function, which is any function that satisfies ${\textstyle \lim _{x\to \infty }L(rx)/L(x)=1}$ for any positive factor r .
[src:complex-systems/power-law] This property of $L(x)$ follows directly from the requirement that $p(x)$ be asymptotically scale invariant; thus, the form of $L(x)$ only controls the shape and finite extent of the lower tail.
[src:complex-systems/power-law] For instance, if $L(x)$ is the constant function, then we have a power law that holds for all values of x .
[src:complex-systems/power-law] In many cases, it is convenient to assume a lower bound $x_{\mathrm {min} }$ from which the law holds.
[src:complex-systems/power-law] where the pre-factor to ${\frac {\alpha -1}{x_{\min }}}$ is the normalizing constant.
[src:complex-systems/power-law] We can now consider several properties of this distribution.
[src:complex-systems/power-law] which is only well defined for $m<\alpha -1$ .
[src:complex-systems/power-law] That is, all moments $m\geq \alpha -1$ diverge: when $\alpha \leq 2$ , the average and all higher-order moments are infinite; when $2<\alpha <3$ , the mean exists, but the variance and higher-order moments are infinite, etc.
[src:complex-systems/power-law] For finite-size samples drawn from such distribution, this behavior implies that the central moment estimators (like the mean and the variance) for diverging moments will never converge – as more data is accumulated, they continue to grow.
[src:complex-systems/power-law] These power-law probability distributions are also called Pareto-type distributions, distributions with Pareto tails, or distributions with regularly varying tails.
[src:complex-systems/power-law] In this distribution, the exponential decay term $\mathrm {e} ^{-\lambda x}$ eventually overwhelms the power-law behavior at very large values of x .
[src:complex-systems/power-law] This distribution does not scale and is thus not asymptotically as a power law; however, it does approximately scale over a finite region before the cutoff.
[src:complex-systems/power-law] The pure form above is a subset of this family, with $\lambda =0$ .
[src:complex-systems/power-law] This distribution is a common alternative to the asymptotic power-law distribution because it naturally captures finite-size effects.
[src:complex-systems/power-law] The Tweedie distributions are a family of statistical models characterized by closure under additive and reproductive convolution as well as under scale transformation.
[src:complex-systems/power-law] Consequently, these models all express a power-law relationship between the variance and the mean.
[src:complex-systems/power-law] These models have a fundamental role as foci of mathematical convergence similar to the role that the normal distribution has as a focus in the central limit theorem.
[src:complex-systems/power-law] This convergence effect explains why the variance-to-mean power law manifests so widely in natural processes, as with Taylor's law in ecology and with fluctuation scaling in physics.
[src:complex-systems/power-law] It can also be shown that this variance-to-mean power law, when demonstrated by the method of expanding bins, implies the presence of 1/*f* noise and that 1/*f* noise can arise as a consequence of this Tweedie convergence effect.
[src:complex-systems/power-law] Although more sophisticated and robust methods have been proposed, the most frequently used graphical methods of identifying power-law probability distributions using random samples are Pareto quantile-quantile plots (or Pareto Q–Q plots), mean residual life plots and log–log plots.
[src:complex-systems/power-law] Another, more robust graphical method uses bundles of residual quantile functions.
[src:complex-systems/power-law] Here, the random sample is called "the data".
[src:complex-systems/power-law] Pareto Q–Q plots compare the quantiles of the log-transformed data to the corresponding quantiles of an exponential distribution with mean 1 (or to the quantiles of a standard Pareto distribution) by plotting the former versus the latter.
[src:complex-systems/power-law] If the resultant scatterplot suggests that the plotted points *asymptotically converge* to a straight line, then a power-law distribution should be suspected.
[src:complex-systems/power-law] A limitation of Pareto Q–Q plots is that they behave poorly when the tail index $\alpha$ (also called Pareto index) is close to 0, because Pareto Q–Q plots are not designed to identify distributions with slowly varying tails.
[src:complex-systems/power-law] If the resultant scatterplot suggests that the plotted points tend to stabilize about a horizontal straight line, then a power-law distribution should be suspected.
[src:complex-systems/power-law] Since the mean residual life plot is very sensitive to outliers (it is not robust), it usually produces plots that are difficult to interpret; for this reason, such plots are usually called Hill horror plots.
[src:complex-systems/power-law] Log–log plots are an alternative way of graphically examining the tail of a distribution using a random sample.
[src:complex-systems/power-law] which forms a straight line with slope k on a log-log scale.
[src:complex-systems/power-law] Caution has to be exercised however as a log–log plot is necessary but insufficient evidence for a power law relationship, as many non power-law distributions will appear as straight lines on a log–log plot.
[src:complex-systems/power-law] This method consists of plotting the logarithm of an estimator of the probability that a particular number of the distribution occurs versus the logarithm of that particular number.
[src:complex-systems/power-law] Usually, this estimator is the proportion of times that the number occurs in the data set.
[src:complex-systems/power-law] If the points in the plot tend to converge to a straight line for large numbers in the x axis, then the researcher concludes that the distribution has a power-law tail.
[src:complex-systems/power-law] Examples of the application of these types of plot have been published.
[src:complex-systems/power-law] A disadvantage of these plots is that, in order for them to provide reliable results, they require huge amounts of data.
[src:complex-systems/power-law] In addition, they are appropriate only for discrete (or grouped) data.
[src:complex-systems/power-law] Another graphical method for the identification of power-law probability distributions using random samples has been proposed.
[src:complex-systems/power-law] This methodology consists of plotting a *bundle for the log-transformed sample*.
[src:complex-systems/power-law] Bundle plots do not have the disadvantages of Pareto Q–Q plots, mean residual life plots and log–log plots mentioned above (they are robust to outliers, allow visually identifying power laws with small values of $\alpha$ , and do not demand the collection of much data).
[src:complex-systems/power-law] In addition, other types of tail behavior can be identified using bundle plots.
[src:complex-systems/power-law] In general, power-law distributions are plotted on doubly logarithmic axes, which emphasizes the upper tail region.
[src:complex-systems/power-law] The cdf is also a power-law function, but with a smaller scaling exponent.
[src:complex-systems/power-law] For data, an equivalent form of the cdf is the rank-frequency approach, in which we first sort the n observed values in ascending order, and plot them against the vector $\left[1,{\frac {n-1}{n}},{\frac {n-2}{n}},\dots ,{\frac {1}{n}}\right]$ .
[src:complex-systems/power-law] Although it can be convenient to log-bin the data, or otherwise smooth the probability density (mass) function directly, these methods introduce an implicit bias in the representation of the data, and thus should be avoided.
[src:complex-systems/power-law] The survival function, on the other hand, is more robust to (but not without) such biases in the data and preserves the linear signature on doubly logarithmic axes.
[src:complex-systems/power-law] Though a survival function representation is favored over that of the pdf while fitting a power law to the data with the linear least square method, it is not devoid of mathematical inaccuracy.
[src:complex-systems/power-law] Thus, while estimating exponents of a power law distribution, maximum likelihood estimator is recommended.
[src:complex-systems/power-law] There are many ways of estimating the value of the scaling exponent for a power-law tail, however not all of them yield unbiased and consistent answers.
[src:complex-systems/power-law] Some of the most reliable techniques are often based on the method of maximum likelihood.
[src:complex-systems/power-law] Alternative methods are often based on making a linear regression on either the log–log probability, the log–log cumulative distribution function, or on log-binned data, but these approaches should be avoided as they can all lead to highly biased estimates of the scaling exponent.
[src:complex-systems/power-law] to the data $x\geq x_{\min }$ , where the coefficient ${\frac {\alpha -1}{x_{\min }}}$ is included to ensure that the distribution is normalized.
[src:complex-systems/power-law] ${\mathcal {L}}(\alpha )=\log \prod _{i=1}^{n}{\frac {\alpha -1}{x_{\min }}}\left({\frac {x_{i}}{x_{\min }}}\right)^{-\alpha }$ The maximum of this likelihood is found by differentiating with respect to parameter $\alpha$ , setting the result equal to zero.
[src:complex-systems/power-law] This estimator exhibits a small finite sample-size bias of order $O(n^{-1})$ , which is small when *n* > 100.
[src:complex-systems/power-law] This estimator is equivalent to the popular Hill estimator from quantitative finance and extreme value theory.
[src:complex-systems/power-law] where $\zeta (\alpha ,x_{\mathrm {min} })$ is the incomplete zeta function.
[src:complex-systems/power-law] The uncertainty in this estimate follows the same formula as for the continuous equation.
[src:complex-systems/power-law] However, the two equations for ${\hat {\alpha }}$ are not equivalent, and the continuous version should not be applied to discrete data, nor vice versa.
[src:complex-systems/power-law] Further, both of these estimators require the choice of $x_{\min }$ .
[src:complex-systems/power-law] For functions with a non-trivial $L(x)$ function, choosing $x_{\min }$ too small produces a significant bias in ${\hat {\alpha }}$ , while choosing it too large increases the uncertainty in ${\hat {\alpha }}$ , and reduces the statistical power of our model.
[src:complex-systems/power-law] In general, the best choice of $x_{\min }$ depends strongly on the particular form of the lower tail, represented by $L(x)$ above.
[src:complex-systems/power-law] More about these methods, and the conditions under which they can be used, can be found in .
[src:complex-systems/power-law] Further, this comprehensive review article provides usable code (Matlab, Python, R and C++) for estimation and testing routines for power-law distributions.
[src:complex-systems/power-law] where $P_{\mathrm {emp} }(x)$ and $P_{\alpha }(x)$ denote the cdfs of the data and the power law with exponent $\alpha$ , respectively.
[src:complex-systems/power-law] As this method does not assume iid data, it provides an alternative way to determine the power-law exponent for data sets in which the temporal correlation can not be ignored.
[src:complex-systems/power-law] Although power-law relations are attractive for many theoretical reasons, demonstrating that data does indeed follow a power-law relation requires more than simply fitting a particular model to the data.
[src:complex-systems/power-law] This is important for understanding the mechanism that gives rise to the distribution: superficially similar distributions may arise for significantly different reasons, and different models yield different predictions, such as extrapolation.
[src:complex-systems/power-law] For example, log-normal distributions are often mistaken for power-law distributions:.
[src:complex-systems/power-law] When you take the log of its probability density function, the log-normal distribution has terms that are constant, log, and log-squared.
[src:complex-systems/power-law] When the mean is small and variance is large, the constant in front of the log-squared term is very small.
[src:complex-systems/power-law] In that case, for most of the distribution, it will be linear on a log-log plot.
[src:complex-systems/power-law] It is only for extreme values that the log-squared term asserts itself and shows that it is not a power-law.
[src:complex-systems/power-law] For example, Gibrat's law about proportional growth processes produce distributions that are lognormal, although their log–log plots look linear over a limited range.
[src:complex-systems/power-law] Therefore, a log–log plot that is slightly "bowed" downwards can reflect a log-normal distribution – not a power law.
[src:complex-systems/power-law] In general, many alternative functional forms can appear to follow a power-law form for some extent.
[src:complex-systems/power-law] Stumpf & Porter (2012) proposed plotting the empirical cumulative distribution function in the log-log domain and claimed that a candidate power-law should cover at least two orders of magnitude.
[src:complex-systems/power-law] Also, researchers usually have to face the problem of deciding whether or not a real-world probability distribution follows a power law.
[src:complex-systems/power-law] As a solution to this problem, Diaz proposed a graphical methodology based on random samples that allow visually discerning between different types of tail behavior.
[src:complex-systems/power-law] This methodology uses bundles of residual quantile functions, also called percentile residual life functions, which characterize many different types of distribution tails, including both heavy and non-heavy tails.
[src:complex-systems/power-law] However, Stumpf & Porter (2012) claimed the need for both a statistical and a theoretical background in order to support a power-law in the underlying mechanism driving the data generating process.
[src:complex-systems/power-law] One method to validate a power-law relation tests many orthogonal predictions of a particular generative mechanism against data.
[src:complex-systems/power-law] Simply fitting a power-law relation to a particular kind of data is not considered a rational approach.
[src:complex-systems/power-law] As such, the validation of power-law claims remains a very active field of research in many areas of modern science.
[src:complex-systems/self-organization] Self-organization is a phenomenon that occurs across various fields, including physics, chemistry, biology, collective behavior, ecology, communication networks, robotics, artificial intelligence, linguistics, social science, urbanism, philosophy, and engineering.
[src:complex-systems/self-organization] Examples of self-organization include crystallization, thermal convection of fluids, chemical oscillation, animal swarming, neural circuits, and black markets.
[src:complex-systems/self-organization] Self-organization is realized in the physics of non-equilibrium processes, and in chemical reactions, where it is often characterized as self-assembly.
[src:complex-systems/self-organization] The concept has proven useful in biology, from the molecular to the ecosystem level.
[src:complex-systems/self-organization] Cited examples of self-organizing behavior also appear in the literature of many other disciplines, both in the natural sciences and in the social sciences (such as economics or anthropology).
[src:complex-systems/self-organization] Self-organization has also been observed in mathematical systems such as cellular automata.
[src:complex-systems/self-organization] Self-organization is an example of the related concept of emergence.
[src:complex-systems/self-organization] The cybernetician William Ross Ashby formulated the original principle of self-organization in 1947.
[src:complex-systems/self-organization] It states that any deterministic dynamic system automatically evolves towards a state of equilibrium that can be described in terms of an attractor in a basin of surrounding states.
[src:complex-systems/self-organization] Once there, the further evolution of the system is constrained to remain in the attractor.
[src:complex-systems/self-organization] This constraint implies a form of mutual dependency or coordination between its constituent components or subsystems.
[src:complex-systems/self-organization] In Ashby's terms, each subsystem has adapted to the environment formed by all other subsystems.
[src:complex-systems/self-organization] The cybernetician Heinz von Foerster formulated the principle of "order from noise" in 1960.
[src:complex-systems/self-organization] It notes that self-organization is facilitated by random perturbations ("noise") that let the system explore a variety of states in its state space.
[src:complex-systems/self-organization] This increases the chance that the system will arrive into the basin of a "strong" or "deep" attractor, from which it then quickly enters the attractor itself.
[src:complex-systems/self-organization] The biophysicist Henri Atlan developed this concept by proposing the principle of "complexity from noise" (French: *le principe de complexité par le bruit*) first in the 1972 book *L'organisation biologique et la théorie de l'information* and then in the 1979 book *Entre le cristal et la fumée*.
[src:complex-systems/self-organization] The physicist and chemist Ilya Prigogine formulated a similar principle as "order through fluctuations" or "order out of chaos".
[src:complex-systems/self-organization] It is applied in the method of simulated annealing for problem solving and machine learning.
[src:complex-systems/self-organization] The idea that the dynamics of a system can lead to an increase in its organization has a long history.
[src:complex-systems/self-organization] The ancient atomists such as Democritus and Lucretius believed that a designing intelligence is unnecessary to create order in nature, arguing that given enough time and space and matter, order emerges by itself.
[src:complex-systems/self-organization] The philosopher René Descartes presents self-organization hypothetically in the fifth part of his 1637 *Discourse on Method*.
[src:complex-systems/self-organization] He elaborated on the idea in his unpublished work *The World*.
[src:complex-systems/self-organization] Immanuel Kant used the term "self-organizing" in his 1790 *Critique of Judgment*, where he argued that teleology is a meaningful concept only if there exists such an entity whose parts or "organs" are simultaneously ends and means.
[src:complex-systems/self-organization] Such a system of organs must be able to behave as if it has a mind of its own, that is, it is capable of governing itself.
[src:complex-systems/self-organization] Sadi Carnot (1796–1832) and Rudolf Clausius (1822–1888) discovered the second law of thermodynamics in the 19th century.
[src:complex-systems/self-organization] It states that total entropy, sometimes understood as disorder, will always increase over time in an isolated system.
[src:complex-systems/self-organization] This means that a system cannot spontaneously increase its order without an external relationship that decreases order elsewhere in the system (e.g. through consuming the low-entropy energy of a battery and diffusing high-entropy heat).
[src:complex-systems/self-organization] 18th-century thinkers had sought to understand the "universal laws of form" to explain the observed forms of living organisms.
[src:complex-systems/self-organization] This idea became associated with Lamarckism and fell into disrepute until the early 20th century, when D'Arcy Wentworth Thompson (1860–1948) attempted to revive it.
[src:complex-systems/self-organization] Ross Ashby introduced the term "self-organizing" to contemporary science in 1947.
[src:complex-systems/self-organization] It was taken up by the cyberneticians Heinz von Foerster, Gordon Pask, Stafford Beer; and von Foerster organized a conference on "The Principles of Self-Organization" at the University of Illinois' Allerton Park in June, 1960 which led to a series of conferences on Self-Organizing Systems.
[src:complex-systems/self-organization] Norbert Wiener took up the idea in the second edition of his *Cybernetics: or Control and Communication in the Animal and the Machine* (1961).
[src:complex-systems/self-organization] Around 2008–2009, a concept of guided self-organization started to take shape.
[src:complex-systems/self-organization] This approach aims to regulate self-organization for specific purposes, so that a dynamical system may reach specific attractors or outcomes.
[src:complex-systems/self-organization] The regulation constrains a self-organizing process within a complex system by restricting local interactions between the system components, rather than following an explicit control mechanism or a global design blueprint.
[src:complex-systems/self-organization] The desired outcomes, such as increases in the resultant internal structure and/or functionality, are achieved by combining task-independent global objectives with task-dependent constraints on local interactions.
[src:complex-systems/self-organization] The many self-organizing phenomena in physics include phase transitions and spontaneous symmetry breaking such as spontaneous magnetization and crystal growth in classical physics, and the laser, superconductivity and Bose–Einstein condensation in quantum physics.
[src:complex-systems/self-organization] Self-organization is found in self-organized criticality in dynamical systems, in tribology, in spin foam systems, and in loop quantum gravity, in plasma, in river basins and deltas, in dendritic solidification (snow flakes), in capillary imbibition and in turbulent structure.
[src:complex-systems/self-organization] The mathematical biologist Stuart Kauffman and other structuralists have suggested that self-organization may play roles alongside natural selection in three areas of evolutionary biology, namely population dynamics, molecular evolution, and morphogenesis.
[src:complex-systems/self-organization] However, this does not take into account the essential role of energy in driving biochemical reactions in cells.
[src:complex-systems/self-organization] The systems of reactions in any cell are self-catalyzing, but not simply self-organizing, as they are thermodynamically open systems relying on a continuous input of energy.
[src:complex-systems/self-organization] Self-organization is not an alternative to natural selection, but it constrains what evolution can do and provides mechanisms such as the self-assembly of membranes which evolution then exploits.
[src:complex-systems/self-organization] Consideration was then extended to short, replicating RNA molecules assumed to be similar to the earliest forms of life in the RNA world.
[src:complex-systems/self-organization] It was shown that the underlying order-generating processes of self-organization in the non-biological systems and in replicating RNA are basically similar.
[src:complex-systems/self-organization] He argues that self-organized systems are often critical systems, with structure spreading out in space and time over every available scale, as shown for example by Per Bak and his collaborators.
[src:complex-systems/self-organization] Therefore, because the distribution of matter in the universe is more or less scale invariant over many orders of magnitude, ideas and strategies developed in the study of self-organized systems could be helpful in tackling certain unsolved problems in cosmology and astrophysics.
[src:complex-systems/self-organization] Phenomena from mathematics and computer science such as cellular automata, random graphs, and some instances of evolutionary computation and artificial life exhibit features of self-organization.
[src:complex-systems/self-organization] In swarm robotics, self-organization is used to produce emergent behavior.
[src:complex-systems/self-organization] In particular the theory of random graphs has been used as a justification for self-organization as a general principle of complex systems.
[src:complex-systems/self-organization] In the field of multi-agent systems, understanding how to engineer systems that are capable of presenting self-organized behavior is an active research area.
[src:complex-systems/self-organization] Optimization algorithms can be considered self-organizing because they aim to find the optimal solution to a problem.
[src:complex-systems/self-organization] If the solution is considered as a state of the iterative system, the optimal solution is the selected, converged structure of the system.
[src:complex-systems/self-organization] Self-organizing networks include small-world networks self-stabilization and scale-free networks.
[src:complex-systems/self-organization] These emerge from bottom-up interactions, unlike top-down hierarchical networks within organizations, which are not self-organizing.
[src:complex-systems/self-organization] Cloud computing systems have been argued to be inherently self-organizing, but while they have some autonomy, they are not self-managing as they do not have the goal of reducing their own complexity.
[src:complex-systems/self-organization] Norbert Wiener regarded the automatic serial identification of a black box and its subsequent reproduction as self-organization in cybernetics.
[src:complex-systems/self-organization] The importance of phase locking or the "attraction of frequencies", as he called it, is discussed in the 2nd edition of his *Cybernetics: Or Control and Communication in the Animal and the Machine*.
[src:complex-systems/self-organization] Eric Drexler sees self-replication as a key step in nano and universal assembly.
[src:complex-systems/self-organization] By contrast, the four concurrently connected galvanometers of W.
