[src:complex-systems/self-organization] Ashby used his state counting measure of variety to describe stable states and produced the "Good Regulator" theorem which requires internal models for self-organized endurance and stability (e.g.
[src:complex-systems/self-organization] Warren McCulloch proposed "Redundancy of Potential Command" as characteristic of the organization of the brain and human nervous system and the necessary condition for self-organization.
[src:complex-systems/self-organization] Heinz von Foerster proposed Redundancy, *R*=1 − *H*/*H*max, where *H* is entropy.
[src:complex-systems/self-organization] In essence this states that unused potential communication bandwidth is a measure of self-organization.
[src:complex-systems/self-organization] In the 1970s Stafford Beer considered self-organization necessary for autonomy in persisting and living systems.
[src:complex-systems/self-organization] He applied his viable system model to management.
[src:complex-systems/self-organization] It consists of five parts: the monitoring of performance of the survival processes (1), their management by recursive application of regulation (2), homeostatic operational control (3) and development (4) which produce maintenance of identity (5) under environmental perturbation.
[src:complex-systems/self-organization] Focus is prioritized by an alerting "algedonic loop" feedback: a sensitivity to both pain and pleasure produced from under-performance or over-performance relative to a standard capability.
[src:complex-systems/self-organization] In the 1990s Gordon Pask argued that von Foerster's H and Hmax were not independent, but interacted via countably infinite recursive concurrent spin processes which he called concepts.
[src:complex-systems/self-organization] His strict definition of concept "a procedure to bring about a relation" permitted his theorem "Like concepts repel, unlike concepts attract" to state a general spin-based principle of self-organization.
[src:complex-systems/self-organization] His edict, an exclusion principle, "There are No Doppelgangers" means no two concepts can be the same.
[src:complex-systems/self-organization] After sufficient time, all concepts attract and coalesce as pink noise.
[src:complex-systems/self-organization] The theory applies to all organizationally closed or homeostatic processes that produce enduring and coherent products which evolve, learn and adapt.
[src:complex-systems/self-organization] The self-organizing behavior of social animals and the self-organization of simple mathematical structures both suggest that self-organization should be expected in human society.
[src:complex-systems/self-organization] Tell-tale signs of self-organization are usually statistical properties shared with self-organizing physical systems.
[src:complex-systems/self-organization] Examples such as critical mass, herd behavior, groupthink and others, abound in sociology, economics, behavioral finance and anthropology.
[src:complex-systems/self-organization] Spontaneous order can be influenced by arousal.
[src:complex-systems/self-organization] In social theory, the concept of self-referentiality has been introduced as a sociological application of self-organization theory by Niklas Luhmann (1984).
[src:complex-systems/self-organization] For Luhmann the elements of a social system are self-producing communications, i.e. a communication produces further communications and hence a social system can reproduce itself as long as there is dynamic communication.
[src:complex-systems/self-organization] For Luhmann, human beings are sensors in the environment of the system.
[src:complex-systems/self-organization] Luhmann developed an evolutionary theory of society and its subsystems, using functional analyses and systems theory.
[src:complex-systems/self-organization] Anarchism can advocate self-organization as one of its basic principles.
[src:complex-systems/self-organization] The market economy is sometimes said to be self-organizing.
[src:complex-systems/self-organization] Paul Krugman has written on the role that market self-organization plays in the business cycle in his book *The Self Organizing Economy*.
[src:complex-systems/self-organization] Friedrich Hayek coined the term *catallaxy* to describe a "self-organizing system of voluntary co-operation", in regards to the spontaneous order of the free market economy.
[src:complex-systems/self-organization] Neo-classical economists hold that imposing central planning usually makes the self-organized economic system less efficient.
[src:complex-systems/self-organization] On the other end of the spectrum, economists consider that market failures are so significant that self-organization produces bad results and that the state should direct production and pricing.
[src:complex-systems/self-organization] Most economists adopt an intermediate position and recommend a mixture of market economy and command economy characteristics (sometimes called a mixed economy).
[src:complex-systems/self-organization] When applied to economics, the concept of self-organization can quickly become ideologically imbued.
[src:complex-systems/self-organization] Enabling others to "learn how to learn" is often taken to mean instructing them how to submit to being taught.
[src:complex-systems/self-organization] Self-organized learning (SOL) denies that "the expert knows best" or that there is ever "the one best method", insisting instead on "the construction of personally significant, relevant and viable meaning" to be tested experientially by the learner.
[src:complex-systems/self-organization] This may be collaborative, and more rewarding personally.
[src:complex-systems/self-organization] It is seen as a lifelong process, not limited to specific learning environments (home, school, university) or under the control of authorities such as parents and professors.
[src:complex-systems/self-organization] It needs to be tested, and intermittently revised, through the personal experience of the learner.
[src:complex-systems/self-organization] It need not be restricted by either consciousness or language.
[src:complex-systems/self-organization] Fritjof Capra argued that it is poorly recognized within psychology and education.
[src:complex-systems/self-organization] It may be related to cybernetics as it involves a negative feedback control loop, or to systems theory.
[src:complex-systems/self-organization] It can be conducted as a learning conversation or dialog between learners or within one person.
[src:complex-systems/self-organization] The self-organizing behavior of drivers in traffic flow determines almost all the spatiotemporal behavior of traffic, such as traffic breakdown at a highway bottleneck, highway capacity, and the emergence of moving traffic jams.
[src:complex-systems/self-organization] These self-organizing effects are explained by Boris Kerner's three-phase traffic theory.
[src:complex-systems/self-organization] Order appears spontaneously in the evolution of language as individual and population behavior interacts with biological evolution.
